Helper¶

Helper functions to handle the sound playing and plotting.

In [3]:
def play_simple_sounds(frequencies, duration=1, sample_rate=44100, plot=True, plot_window_size_nth=400, fun=np.sin):
    legend_data = []
    for frequency in frequencies:
        print(f'Playing at {frequency} Hz.')
        legend_data.append(f'{frequency} Hz')
        
        # time from 0 ... seconds in seconds * fs steps, i.e. stepsize 1/fs
        t = np.linspace(0, duration, duration * fs, False)

        # sounds as a time series of numbers ... your playground :-)
        sound = fun(frequency * t * 2 * np.pi) 

        # scale to make sure that highest value is within 16-bit range
        sound = sound * (2**15 - 1) / np.max(np.abs(sound))

        # convert to 16-bit data
        sound = sound.astype(np.int16)

        # start playback
        play_obj = sa.play_buffer(sound, 1, 2, fs)

        # wait until playback is finished
        play_obj.wait_done()
        
        # plot
        plt.plot(t[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)], sound[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)])
        
    plt.legend(legend_data, bbox_to_anchor=(1.04,1), loc="upper left")
    if plot:
        plt.show()
In [4]:
def play_superpositioned_sounds(frequencies, duration=1, sample_rate=44100, plot=True, plot_window_size_nth=400):
    legend_data = []
    sounds = []
    
    # time from 0 ... seconds in seconds * fs steps, i.e. stepsize 1/fs
    t = np.linspace(0, duration, duration * fs, False)

    # sounds as a time series of numbers ... your playground :-)
    sound = np.sin(0 * t * 2 * np.pi) 
    for frequency in frequencies:
        addition = (1/len(frequencies)) * np.sin(frequency * t * 2 * np.pi) 
        # scale to make sure that highest value is within 16-bit range
        addition = addition * (2**15 - 1) / np.max(np.abs(addition))
        # convert to 16-bit data
        addition = addition.astype(np.int16)
        sound = sound + addition
        sounds.append(addition)
        legend_data.append(f'{frequency} Hz')
    
    legend_data.append(f'Superpositioned')
    # scale to make sure that highest value is within 16-bit range
    sound = sound * (2**15 - 1) / np.max(np.abs(sound))

    # convert to 16-bit data
    sound = sound.astype(np.int16)

    # start playback
    play_obj = sa.play_buffer(sound, 1, 2, fs)

    # wait until playback is finished
    play_obj.wait_done()

    # plot
    if plot:
        for i, _ in enumerate(frequencies):
            plt.plot(t[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)], sounds[i][:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)])
        plt.plot(t[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)], sound[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)], linestyle='dotted')
        plt.legend(legend_data, bbox_to_anchor=(1.04,1), loc="upper left")
        plt.show()
In [5]:
def play_modified_sounds(frequencies, duration=1, sample_rate=44100, plot=True, plot_window_size_nth=400, modfun=lambda x: x):
    legend_data = []
    for frequency in frequencies:
        print(f'Playing at {frequency} Hz.')
        legend_data.append(f'{frequency} Hz')
        
        # time from 0 ... seconds in seconds * fs steps, i.e. stepsize 1/fs
        t = np.linspace(0, duration, duration * fs, False)

        # sounds as a time series of numbers ... your playground :-)
        sound = modfun(np.sin(frequency * t * 2 * np.pi))

        # scale to make sure that highest value is within 16-bit range
        sound = sound * (2**15 - 1) / np.max(np.abs(sound))
        
        # convert to 16-bit data
        sound = sound.astype(np.int16)

        # start playback
        play_obj = sa.play_buffer(sound, 1, 2, fs)

        # wait until playback is finished
        play_obj.wait_done()
        
        # plot
        plt.plot(t[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)], sound[:int(len(t)/plot_window_size_nth)])
        
    plt.legend(legend_data, bbox_to_anchor=(1.04,1), loc="upper left")
    if plot:
        plt.show()

Submission¶

Trying different frequencies¶

First we try some different frequencies to see the outcome.

In [6]:
frequencies = [100, 200, 400, 440, 445, 500, 1000, 2000]  # each frequency to go through
play_simple_sounds(frequencies)

Playing at 100 Hz.
Playing at 200 Hz.
Playing at 400 Hz.
Playing at 440 Hz.
Playing at 445 Hz.
Playing at 500 Hz.
Playing at 1000 Hz.
Playing at 2000 Hz.

Logically, the steps where the frequency gets doubled compared to the previous frequency are easily to be distinguished. Interestingely enough, I think I can hear the difference from 400 to 440 compared to 440 to 445. However, this is still quite hard.

To me it is very interesting to see, that we only need a slight increase in frequency in the lower areas to have a substantially different sound (tested frequencies 100, 200, 400), whereas in the higher areas we will need much larger jumps (tested frequencies 500, 1000, 2000) in order to achieve the same result.

Interestingely, we on the plot above, we can see a not so smooth curve on the frequency 2000Hz. This might be due to the samplerate, but also potential just a plot artifact.

Superposition¶

First we try to superposition frequencies which are close by each other to see whether we can hear a difference.

In [8]:
play_superpositioned_sounds([450, 440, 430])

Superpositioning the frequencies let's us hear the differences of the frequencies (oscillating). We can also see that adding up the numbers, we will technically end up at the same frequency (mean) of 440 Hz. Obviously, since we hear an oscillation the sound does not equal to 440 Hz. In reality the sound is jumping back and fourth between the 3 frequencies.

Next up, we want to superposition the same tone in different pitches.

In [9]:
play_superpositioned_sounds([880, 440, 220],plot_window_size_nth=200)

Superpositioning the same tone (in our case a concert-pitch A), will result in a nice harmonic sound.

Next up, we want to see what happens, if we superposition one sound with the inverse of itself.

In [10]:
play_superpositioned_sounds([440, 440*-1])

As expected, there is no sound being played and the resulting wave of the superposition is 0. In other words, opposing waves cancel each other out. We can verfiy this by slightly altering one of the frequencies.

In [11]:
play_superpositioned_sounds([440, 441*-1])

This time we can hear sound again. Lastly, we want to try one final thing using superposition, which is random numbers. We would expect, that if we put a bunch of random variables into superposition, we would get white noise. White noise is basically the absence of structure, in other words pure randomness. Let's see if we can achieve white noise using different input sizes.

In [12]:
play_superpositioned_sounds(np.random.randint(low=100, high=8000, size=10), plot=False)

This first attempt with a sample size of 10 is not yet so great.

In [13]:
play_superpositioned_sounds(np.random.randint(low=100, high=8000, size=100), plot=False)

It is still not great so we will have to go much bigger.

In [14]:
play_superpositioned_sounds(np.random.randint(low=100, high=8000, size=1000), plot=False)

This now sounds more like it, we can hear now the characteristic "sound" of white noise.

Different Shapes: Square¶

We have seen sine waves. Now we want to try to build different shapes. We will try to build a squared shape. By definition, the squared shape is implemented using the sign function. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_wave

In [15]:
play_modified_sounds([440], modfun=np.sign)

Playing at 440 Hz.

We can verify this by comparing it to the reference implementation of scipy. https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/signal.html#waveforms

In [16]:
play_modified_sounds([440], modfun=signal.square)

Playing at 440 Hz.

This looks good. There are many more shapes that can be computed such as sawtooth wave and triangle wave (which is simply the sawtooth with the abs function applied on top of it).
